text.b: Mr. Michael A. Boggio Jr, AIA

page.text: This memorandum presents the results of a Traffic Impact Assessment (TIA) for the proposed Flagstar Bank
in the City of Ann Arbor, Michigan. The project site is located on the south side of Plymouth Road
approximately 700 feet east of Green Road and is currently vacant. The proposed development plans include
a new 2,840 square feet (SF) Flagstar Bank with access provided via connection to a shared access roadway
that has driveways to Plymouth Road and Green Road. Currently, egress left turns are prohibited from the
shared access driveway to Plymouth Road. Plymouth Road and Green Road are under the jurisdiction of the
The City of Ann Arbor has required a TIA to evaluate traffic operations with the proposed project. This TIA
has been completed to identify the impacts (if any) of this project on the intersection of Plymouth Road &
Green Road and the site access points. The scope of this study was developed based on Fleis &
VandenBrink Engineering, Inc.’s. (F&V) knowledge of the study area, understanding of the development
program, accepted traffic engineering practice, and methodologies published by the Institute of Transportation
Engineers (ITE). Input and agreement on the study scope was also achieved through conversations with the
City’s Traffic Engineer. The study analyses were completed using Synchro and SimTraffic, Version 8 traffic
Existing weekday traffic volume data were collected by F&V on August 12
movement counts were collected at the study intersections during the AM (7:00 AM to 9:00 AM) and PM (4:00
PM to 6:00 PM) peak periods. F&V also collected an inventory of existing lane use and traffic controls and
obtained existing traffic signal timing information from the City of Ann Arbor. The applicable data referenced
The existing AM and PM peak hour traffic volumes were identified based on the data collected. Existing peak
hour vehicle delays and Levels of Service (LOS) were calculated at the study intersections based on the
existing lane use and traffic control, the existing peak hour traffic volumes, and the methodologies presented
in the Highway Capacity Manual, 2000 (HCM). Typically, LOS D is considered acceptable, with LOS A

representing minimal delay, and LOS F indicating failing conditions. Additionally, SimTraffic network
simulations were reviewed to evaluate network operations and vehicle queues. The results of the existing
conditions analysis are attached and summarized in Table 1.
The results of the existing conditions analysis indicate that all study intersection approaches currently operate
acceptably at a LOS D or better during both peak periods. Review of network simulations indicates that the
intersection of Plymouth Road & Green Road currently experiences a long westbound and eastbound vehicle
queue during the AM and PM peak hours, respectively; however, these queues dissipate and are not present
throughout the duration of the peak periods.
Vehicle queue lengths from the signalized intersection of Plymouth Road & Green Road were also calculated
and evaluated with respect to the existing driveway location on Green Road. The northbound queue length is
critical to access for both ingress and egress movements. The queue length calculations based on Synchro
and SimTraffic simulations are shown in Table 2. The storage length is also indicated to be the distance
between the painted stop bar and the driveway. The results of the queue length analysis indicate that the
driveway is periodically blocked during the PM peak period. However, observation of the SimTraffic network

percentile queue length is infrequent with minimal conflict
between this queue and site traffic.
As this development is proposed within the next year, and based on stagnant traffic growth patterns
throughout southeast Michigan, future background conditions without the proposed development are
assumed to be equal to existing conditions.
The number of AM and PM peak hour vehicle trips that would be generated by the proposed Flagstar Bank
was forecast based on data published by the Institute of Transportation Engineers (ITE) in
Edition and the Trip Generation Handbook, 2
As is typical of Banks, a portion of the site-generated trips are already present on the adjacent road network
and are interrupted to visit the site. These trips are known as “pass-by” trips and account for a percentage of
the total site-generated traffic. Pass-by trips result in turning movements at the site driveways, but do not
increase traffic volumes on the adjacent road network. The site trip generation forecast is shown in Table 3.
The vehicle trips that would be generated by the proposed development were assigned to the study road
network based on existing peak hour traffic patterns, the proposed site access plan, and the methodologies
published by ITE. This methodology indicates that pass-by trips enter and exit the development in their
original direction of travel, while new trips will return to their direction of origin. The assumed distribution of
site traffic is summarized in Table 4.
1. Pass-by trip percentage not available for the AM peak hour, therefore, assumed equal to the PM peak hour rate.

The site-generated trip assignments were added to the existing traffic volumes to determine the total future
peak hour traffic volumes with the proposed development. Future peak hour vehicle delays and LOS were
calculated at the study intersections based on these volumes and the existing intersection lane use and traffic
control. The results of the future conditions analysis are attached and summarized in Table 5.
Ann Arbor Flagstar TIA DRAFT Memo 8-19-14
The results of this analysis indicate that the proposed project would not have a significant impact on the study
intersections. Future vehicle delays and LOS as shown in Table 5 would be similar to existing conditions and
any increases would not be discernable. Additionally, all movements at the proposed driveway would operate
acceptably at a LOS B or better during both peak periods.
Vehicle queue lengths from the signalized intersection of Plymouth Road & Green Road were once again
calculated and evaluated with respect to the existing driveway location on Green Road. The results of this
analysis indicate that vehicle queue lengths would be similar to existing conditions and would increase by less
than 20 feet (0-1 vehicles) during both peak periods, as shown in Table 6.
Currently, the driveway is being proposed south of the two-way cross road located in the median of the
shared access driveway to Plymouth Road; however, the City has indicated they would prefer the driveway to
align with the two-way cross road. Therefore, vehicle queue lengths were calculated with respect to the
proposed site driveway connection to the existing shared access driveway. The results of the evaluation
indicate that if aligned with the cross road, the driveway would be blocked approximately 32% of the PM peak
hour, whereas if located south of the cross road, the driveway would only be blocked approximately 25% of
the PM peak hour. Therefore, the driveway should be located south of the cross road to improve site access.
The conclusions of this Traffic Impact Assessment are as follows:
1. Currently, all study intersection approaches operate acceptably at a LOS D or better during both peak
2. Vehicle queues from the Plymouth Road & Green Road intersection currently periodically block the
shared access driveway to Green Road; however, the blockage is infrequent with minimal conflict
between this queue and site traffic.
3. Future traffic operations with the proposed Flagstar Bank will be similar to existing conditions and
minor changes to vehicle delay and LOS will not be discernable.
4. Connection to the shared access roadway should be located south of the two-way cross road in the
median of the Plymouth Road driveway to improve site access.
